Part 1

In this exercise we will plot the Gini index in 2019 for as many countries as possible. To solve the exercise, go through the following steps.

  • Download data on the Gini Index from the World Bank, load it into R, and clean the dataset.

  • Construct the plots below for your assigned country.

  • Construct the plot below for all the countries with available data on the Gini coefficient for 2019. Hint: The commands ggplot(df, aes(x=reorder(country, gini), y=gini)), geom_linerange(aes(ymin=0, ymax=gini, alpha = 0.8)) and coord_flip() might be useful.



Part 2

In this exercise, we will consider the change in the Gini coefficients for the countries in our dataset.

  • Create a new dataset where you keep all the years. Clean the dataset and keep the columns with the years and country names.

  • Change the shape of the dataset from wide to long. Hint: Use some version of gather(year, gini, 2:65) from the dplyr library.

  • Construct the chart below. Let the vertical line denote the change for your assigned country.
